  "why": "The paper uses realistic, semantically-meaningful image transformations (brightness, contrast, blur, rain, fog, affine transforms) and an explicit metamorphic oracle (Equation 2) that assumes transformed inputs should remain semantically equivalent to seeds. It also applies an MSE-based filtration check relative to the original seed (Equation 3) to avoid false positives for many simple transforms. However, DeepTest composes transformations via a coverage-guided, depth-first search (Algorithm 1) that incrementally mutates previously-generated images and does not enforce global similarity constraints to the original seed across iterations; furthermore the authors explicitly state they do not apply the filtration criterion for composite transformations or guided-search outputs. Thus the tool enforces plausibility/semantic-preservation only partially (effectively between recent mutation steps or for selected/simple transforms) and does not account for cumulative distortion across iterative combinations, matching the definition of Medium.",
